      Just
        "a daemon takes http requests and makes a get(id) call to rethink. Inevitably, the calls to get(id).run() would begin to never call the callback function. I have a simple case here:\n\n```\nvar r = require('rethinkdb');\n\nr.connect({host:'localhost', port:28015, db:'cointhink', timeout: 1},\n  function(err, conn) {\n\n  var get_count = 0\n  var id = 'donpdonp/buynext'\n\n  for(var i=0; i < 1000; i++) { load_fast() }\n\n  function load_fast(){\n    get_count += 1\n    console.log((new Date().toISOString())+' rethink load '+id+' get_count '+get_count)\n    r.table('scripts').get(id).run(conn, function(err, doc){\n      get_count -= 1\n      console.log('rethink loaded '+id+'. get_count remaining '+get_count)\n    })\n  }\n})\n```\n\nInstead of seeing 1000 load messages followed by 1000 'loaded' messages, The output is 1000 load messages followed by one 'loaded' message, and the script never finishes.\n\nnode v0.10.10\nrethinkdb@1.7.0-1\nrethinkdb 1.7.1-0ubuntu1~raring (GCC 4.7.3)\n"
